---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Med-Surgical 23 — Lou Thao"
  description="Unfolding case study: Postoperative Colon Resection and Patient-Controlled Analgesia (PCA) (MED-23)"
>

  <div class="breadcrumb">
    <a href={base}>Home</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <a href={`${base}cases/`}>Cases</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <a href={`${base}cases/med-surgical/`}>Med-Surgical</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <span>Med-Surgical 23 — Lou Thao</span>
  </div>

  <div class="case-header">
    <span class="card-tag">GI / Postoperative</span>
    <h1>Med-Surgical 23 — Lou Thao</h1>
    <p class="case-subtitle">Postoperative Colon Resection and Patient-Controlled Analgesia (PCA)</p>
    <div class="case-meta">
      <span>👤 Lou Thao, Female</span>
      <span>⏱ Scenario: 20–25 minutes</span>
      <span>💬 Debrief: 20–25 minutes</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout callout-info">
    <strong>📖 How to Use This Unfolding Case Study</strong>
    <p>Work through each phase in order. Information is revealed progressively — exactly as it would be in a real clinical encounter. Before reading each answer, pause and reason through the question yourself. Use the <strong>▶ Reveal Answer</strong> toggles to check your thinking.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- PHASE 1 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase1">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 1</span>
      <h2>You Arrive at the Bedside</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">You are the postoperative nurse receiving Lou Thao from the PACU. She has returned from colon resection surgery. The PCA pump is running and connected to her IV. Her family is in the waiting room.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>📋 Handoff Report</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Patient</th><td>Lou Thao</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Gender</th><td>Female</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Primary Dx</th><td>Post-operative colon resection (abdominal surgery)</td></tr>
            <tr><th>PCA</th><td>Morphine PCA running — demand dose 1 mg q10 min lockout</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Allergies</th><td>NKDA (No Known Drug Allergies)</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Code Status</th><td>Full code</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>💊 Medications on MAR</h3>
        <ul class="med-list">
          <li><strong>Morphine Sulfate PCA</strong> — 1 mg demand dose · 10-min lockout · IV (Schedule II HIGH ALERT)</li>
          <li><strong>Azithromycin (Zithromax) 500 mg</strong> — IV Piggyback (IVPB) q24h</li>
          <li><strong>Acetaminophen</strong> — PO · Adjunct pain management</li>
          <li><strong>IV fluids</strong> — IV hydration / fluid maintenance</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="scene-box">
      <h3>🛡️ SWIPE Safety Check — Entering the Room</h3>
      <table class="data-table">
        <tbody>
          <tr><th>S — Siderails</th><td>Both siderails up</td></tr>
          <tr><th>W — Wristband</th><td>Two identifiers confirmed (name + date of birth)</td></tr>
          <tr><th>I — IV / PCA</th><td>IV site patent, PCA pump settings verified, tubing intact</td></tr>
          <tr><th>P — Pull cord</th><td>Call light within reach; patient instructed to call before ambulating</td></tr>
          <tr><th>E — Equipment</th><td>PCA pump functioning; <strong>naloxone (Narcan) at bedside</strong></td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <div class="callout callout-warning">
      <strong>⚠️ HIGH ALERT: PCA Pump Verification — Two-Nurse Check Required</strong>
      <p>Morphine PCA is a HIGH ALERT medication. Before patient use, perform a two-nurse independent verification:</p>
      <ol style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0 1.25rem;">
        <li>Verify patient identity — two identifiers</li>
        <li>Compare provider order with pump programming: drug name, concentration, demand dose (1 mg), lockout interval (10 min), 4-hour limit</li>
        <li>Inspect tubing — no air bubbles, kinks, or disconnections</li>
        <li>Confirm anti-siphon valve in place</li>
        <li>Document verification with co-signature of both nurses</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: Why does PCA require a two-nurse verification?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Why two-nurse verification for PCA:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Morphine is a Schedule II opioid — programming errors can result in respiratory depression, cardiac arrest, and death</li>
          <li>An independent check catches errors that a single nurse might overlook (decimal point errors, wrong concentration, incorrect lockout interval)</li>
          <li>The Joint Commission identifies PCA programming errors as a leading cause of medication-related deaths in hospitals</li>
          <li>Double-checking also verifies the physical setup: correct tubing, no bypasses, proper connections</li>
          <li><strong>Bottom line:</strong> The lockout interval is a safety mechanism — but only if it is programmed correctly. Two nurses verify it works as designed.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ PCA verified. You now focus on respiratory and sedation monitoring…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 2 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase2">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 2</span>
      <h2>PCA Safety and Respiratory Monitoring</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">Lou's PCA has been running for 30 minutes. She appears drowsy but responds to her name. You prepare to perform your focused opioid-safety assessment.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>💉 PCA Settings Summary</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Parameter</th><th>Lou Thao's Setting</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Drug</td><td>Morphine sulfate</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Demand (bolus) dose</td><td>1 mg</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Lockout interval</td><td>10 minutes</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Maximum dose / 4 hours</td><td>20 mg</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Background infusion</td><td>None ordered</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>😴 POSS Sedation Scale</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Score</th><th>Level</th><th>Action</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><strong>S</strong></td><td>Sleep — easy to arouse</td><td>Acceptable</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>1</strong></td><td>Awake and alert</td><td>Acceptable</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>2</strong></td><td>Slightly drowsy — easy to arouse</td><td>Acceptable</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>3</strong></td><td>Frequently drowsy — difficult to arouse</td><td>HOLD PCA · Notify provider</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>4</strong></td><td>Unresponsive — cannot arouse</td><td>EMERGENCY — naloxone</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="scene-box">
      <h3>🫁 Respiratory Monitoring Protocol</h3>
      <table class="data-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Parameter</th><th>Normal</th><th>Concern</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Respiratory rate (RR)</td><td>12–20 breaths/min</td><td>&lt; 10 breaths/min — HOLD PCA</td></tr>
          <tr><td>SpO₂</td><td>≥ 94%</td><td>&lt; 90% — intervene immediately</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Sedation score</td><td>S, 1, or 2</td><td>Score 3–4 — HOLD PCA · Notify provider</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p style="margin-top: 0.75rem; font-size: 0.9rem;"><strong>Key principle:</strong> Sedation increases <em>before</em> respiratory rate drops. Assess sedation level first — it is the earliest warning sign of opioid overdose.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="callout callout-danger">
      <strong>🚨 PCA by Proxy — A Fatal Error</strong>
      <p><strong>ONLY the patient may press the PCA button.</strong> If a family member, nurse, or visitor presses the button while Lou is sleeping or unable to respond, the built-in safety mechanism (self-limiting sedation) is bypassed. "PCA by proxy" has caused respiratory depression, cardiac arrest, and death. Educate Lou and her family clearly: <em>"Only Lou presses this button. If she is asleep, do not press it for her."</em></p>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: Lou's RR is 8 and she is difficult to arouse (POSS score 3). What do you do?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Priority actions — opioid-induced respiratory depression:</strong></p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>STOP the PCA pump immediately</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Stimulate the patient</strong> — call her name loudly, sternal rub</li>
          <li><strong>Apply supplemental oxygen</strong> — nasal cannula or mask</li>
          <li><strong>Assess SpO₂ and vital signs</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Administer naloxone (Narcan) 0.4–2 mg IV</strong> — per standing order or as prescribed; titrate every 2–3 min as needed</li>
          <li><strong>Call for help / activate rapid response</strong> if unresponsive</li>
          <li><strong>Document</strong> all findings, interventions, and patient response</li>
          <li><strong>Notify provider</strong> — do not restart PCA without new order</li>
        </ol>
        <p><strong>Remember:</strong> Naloxone has a shorter half-life than morphine. Lou may become sedated again as naloxone wears off — monitor closely for re-sedation for at least 1 hour.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ Respiratory assessment complete. Lou's sedation score is 2 and RR is 14. You now assess pain…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 3 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase3">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 3</span>
      <h2>Pain Assessment and Patient Education</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">Lou is awake and tells you her pain is a 6/10. She says, "I've been waiting for it to get worse before pressing the button. I don't want to be a bother." Her last demand dose was 45 minutes ago.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>📊 Numeric Pain Scale</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Score</th><th>Interpretation</th><th>Goal</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>0</td><td>No pain</td><td rowspan="3" style="vertical-align: middle;">Adequate control: ≤ 3–4/10 at rest</td></tr>
            <tr><td>1–3</td><td>Mild pain</td></tr>
            <tr><td>4–6</td><td>Moderate pain — <strong>intervene now</strong></td></tr>
            <tr><td>7–10</td><td>Severe pain — do not wait to treat</td><td>Undertreated; complications likely</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>📚 PCA Patient Education for Lou</h3>
        <ul class="med-list">
          <li>Press the button when pain is a <strong>3–4/10</strong> — don't wait for 7–8</li>
          <li>Press it <strong>10 minutes before</strong> coughing, deep breathing, or getting up</li>
          <li>The lockout interval <strong>protects you</strong> from overdose — you cannot receive too much</li>
          <li><strong>Only YOU press the button</strong> — not family, not nurses</li>
          <li>Tell the nurse if pain is not controlled after pressing 2–3 times</li>
          <li>Common side effects: drowsiness, nausea, constipation, itching — report all</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: Why does undertreated pain lead to postoperative complications?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Consequences of undertreated postoperative pain:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Atelectasis and pneumonia:</strong> Pain causes shallow breathing and splinting. Patients avoid deep breaths and coughing → secretions pool → alveoli collapse (atelectasis) → pneumonia risk increases</li>
          <li><strong>Deep Vein Thrombosis (DVT):</strong> Uncontrolled pain immobilizes patients. Immobility → venous stasis → clot formation in lower extremities</li>
          <li><strong>Prolonged hospital stay:</strong> Patients who cannot participate in early ambulation, deep breathing, or incentive spirometry have slower recovery trajectories</li>
          <li><strong>Chronic pain development:</strong> Poorly managed acute postoperative pain increases the risk of transitioning to chronic pain syndromes</li>
          <li><strong>Bottom line:</strong> Adequate pain control is not comfort only — it is a clinical necessity that enables every other postoperative intervention to succeed</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ Lou's pain is now 3/10 after pressing the PCA. You assess her GI recovery and wound…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 4 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase4">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 4</span>
      <h2>GI Recovery and Wound Assessment</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">It is postoperative day 1. Lou has had no oral intake. She reports abdominal fullness. You auscultate her abdomen and inspect the incision.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🔊 Bowel Sound Auscultation</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Finding</th><th>Significance</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Absent bowel sounds — all 4 quadrants</td><td>Expected Day 0–1 post-abdominal surgery — paralytic ileus</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Hypoactive (&lt; 1/min)</td><td>GI motility returning — continue monitoring</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Active (5–15/min)</td><td>Normal — GI recovery progressing</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Passage of flatus</td><td><strong>First sign of GI recovery</strong> — precedes resumption of oral diet</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p style="margin-top: 0.5rem; font-size: 0.85rem;"><strong>Technique:</strong> Auscultate all 4 quadrants for at least 1 minute each <em>before</em> palpation (palpation can stimulate or suppress sounds).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🩹 REEDA Wound Assessment</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Letter</th><th>Assessment</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><strong>R</strong></td><td>Redness — erythema at wound edges</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>E</strong></td><td>Edema — swelling around incision</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>E</strong></td><td>Ecchymosis — bruising</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>D</strong></td><td>Discharge — type, amount, odor (serous normal; purulent = infection)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>A</strong></td><td>Approximation — wound edges together and intact?</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="scene-box">
      <h3>💧 Fluid Volume Deficit — Recognition (MED-24)</h3>
      <table class="data-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Sign / Symptom</th><th>Significance</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Urine output &lt; 30 mL/hr</td><td>Earliest and most reliable sign — kidney compensates</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Dark yellow / amber urine</td><td>Concentrated urine — kidneys retaining fluid</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Tachycardia</td><td>Compensatory response to decreased circulating volume</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Hypotension (especially orthostatic)</td><td>Late sign — significant volume already lost</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Dry mucous membranes</td><td>Visible sign of dehydration</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Weight loss</td><td>1 kg = 1 liter fluid deficit</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: How is paralytic ileus managed?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Paralytic ileus management:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>NPO (nothing by mouth)</strong> — bowel must rest; no oral intake until flatus is passed and bowel sounds return</li>
          <li><strong>Early ambulation</strong> — most effective non-pharmacological intervention for stimulating GI motility; ambulate day 0 if hemodynamically stable</li>
          <li><strong>IV fluid maintenance</strong> — maintains hydration and electrolyte balance during NPO period</li>
          <li><strong>Nasogastric (NG) tube</strong> — if abdominal distension is severe; decompresses stomach</li>
          <li><strong>Minimize opioids</strong> — opioids suppress GI motility; use multimodal analgesia (acetaminophen, NSAIDs) to reduce opioid requirements</li>
          <li><strong>Chewing gum</strong> — stimulates cephalic-vagal reflex and GI motility (evidence-based, low-risk)</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor:</strong> Report absence of bowel sounds beyond 72 hours or worsening distension to provider</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ Lou has passed flatus. Diet progression can begin. You prepare discharge education…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 5 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase5">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 5</span>
      <h2>Patient Education for Recovery</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">Lou asks, "When can I eat regular food? Can I go home soon? What do I need to do to get better faster?" You sit down to provide structured postoperative recovery education.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🥣 Diet Progression After Colon Resection</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Stage</th><th>Criteria to Advance</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><strong>NPO</strong></td><td>Until flatus passed + bowel sounds return</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Clear liquids</strong></td><td>Tolerating clear liquids without nausea/vomiting</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Full liquids / soft</strong></td><td>No abdominal distension; tolerating clear liquids</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Regular diet</strong></td><td>Full bowel function restored; no complications</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🚶 Early Ambulation Protocol</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Postoperative Day</th><th>Activity Goal</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Day 0 (day of surgery)</td><td>Dangle at bedside 1–2× if hemodynamically stable</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Day 1</td><td>Walk in hallway with assistance; 2–3× daily</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Day 2+</td><td>Increase distance and independence each day</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Home</td><td>No heavy lifting for 6–8 weeks; progressive activity</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="scene-box">
      <h3>🫁 Incentive Spirometry and Wound Care Teaching</h3>
      <table class="data-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Topic</th><th>Instruction</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Incentive spirometry</td><td>Use 10 breaths every hour while awake; hold each breath 3–5 seconds at peak</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Cough and deep breathe</td><td>Splint abdomen with a pillow; cough deeply every 2 hours</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Wound care at home</td><td>Keep incision dry for 48 hours; no submerging in water; pat dry after shower</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Signs of infection — call provider</td><td>Redness spreading, warmth, increasing pain, purulent drainage, fever &gt; 38°C (100.4°F)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Activity restrictions</td><td>No heavy lifting (&gt; 10 lbs) for 6–8 weeks; no driving while on opioids</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: How does each intervention prevent a specific complication?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Intervention</th><th>Complication Prevented</th><th>Mechanism</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Incentive spirometry + deep breathing</td><td>Atelectasis, pneumonia</td><td>Re-expands collapsed alveoli; mobilizes secretions</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Early ambulation</td><td>DVT, pulmonary embolism, ileus</td><td>Venous compression with leg muscles; stimulates GI motility</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Adequate pain control</td><td>Atelectasis, immobility, DVT</td><td>Allows deep breathing, coughing, and ambulation</td></tr>
            <tr><td>No lifting 6–8 weeks</td><td>Incisional hernia, wound dehiscence</td><td>Abdominal fascia requires 6–8 weeks for full tensile strength</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Diet progression</td><td>Aspiration, ileus, bowel obstruction</td><td>Allows GI tract to resume function safely and progressively</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ Education complete. You finalize your nursing diagnoses and prepare your SBAR…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 6 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase6">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 6</span>
      <h2>Priority Nursing Diagnoses + SBAR</h2>
    </div>
    <h3>📋 Priority Nursing Diagnoses</h3>
    <div class="dx-rank-list">
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">1</span>
        <div><strong>Acute Pain</strong><div class="dx-aeb">r/t surgical tissue disruption secondary to colon resection AEB: patient-reported pain 6/10, guarded positioning, reluctance to cough and deep breathe</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">2</span>
        <div><strong>Risk for Respiratory Depression</strong><div class="dx-aeb">r/t opioid administration via morphine PCA AEB: morphine PCA in use; sedation monitoring required every 1–2 hours</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">3</span>
        <div><strong>Risk for Infection</strong><div class="dx-aeb">r/t surgical wound from abdominal colon resection AEB: abdominal incision present; bowel surgery carries contamination risk</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">4</span>
        <div><strong>Risk for Fluid Volume Deficit</strong><div class="dx-aeb">r/t NPO status, surgical blood loss, and wound drainage AEB: postoperative; limited oral intake; IV fluids as only source of hydration</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">5</span>
        <div><strong>Deficient Knowledge</strong><div class="dx-aeb">r/t PCA operation, wound care, activity restrictions, and diet progression AEB: patient stated she was waiting for severe pain before pressing PCA button</div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ SBAR — Calling the Provider About Lou Thao</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <div class="sbar-block">
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-s"><span class="sbar-label">S — Situation</span><p>Calling about Lou Thao, a postoperative colon resection patient on morphine PCA. I am concerned because her pain is not fully controlled with current settings and her urine output has been less than 30 mL/hr for 2 hours.</p></div>
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-b"><span class="sbar-label">B — Background</span><p>She is postoperative day 1 from colon resection. She is currently receiving morphine PCA (1 mg demand dose, 10-minute lockout), azithromycin IV, and acetaminophen PO. Allergies: NKDA. Current vitals: [insert].</p></div>
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-a"><span class="sbar-label">A — Assessment</span><p>She is rating pain at 6/10 despite PCA use. POSS sedation score is 2. SpO₂ is 96% on room air. RR is 14 breaths/min. Urine output in the last 2 hours: 45 mL total (22.5 mL/hr). Urine is dark amber. Bowel sounds absent in all quadrants — expected on Day 1.</p></div>
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-r"><span class="sbar-label">R — Recommendation</span><p>Requesting evaluation of PCA settings — consider increasing demand dose. Also requesting IV fluid bolus order for low urine output and BMP to assess renal function and electrolytes. Shall I proceed with anything in the meantime?</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <!-- APPENDIX A: Medications -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="appendix-a">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Appendix A</span>
      <h2>Medication Review</h2>
    </div>
    <table class="data-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Medication</th><th>Class</th><th>Key Nursing Points</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Morphine Sulfate PCA</strong> <span class="badge-danger">HIGH ALERT</span></td>
          <td>Opioid analgesic — Schedule II</td>
          <td>Binds mu-opioid receptors → inhibits CNS pain transmission. Settings: 1 mg demand, 10-min lockout, 20 mg max/4 hr. Onset IV: 5–15 min; peak: 30 min. Side effects: respiratory depression ⚠️, sedation, constipation, N/V, pruritus, urinary retention. Antidote: naloxone 0.4–2 mg IV. Two-nurse verification required before use.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Azithromycin (Zithromax) 500 mg IVPB</strong></td>
          <td>Macrolide antibiotic</td>
          <td>Inhibits bacterial protein synthesis. Infuse over 1 hour (500 mg in 250 mL = 250 mL/hr). Do NOT give as IV push. Side effects: nausea, abdominal pain, diarrhea, QT prolongation (monitor ECG in at-risk patients). Report palpitations. Complete full course.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Acetaminophen PO</strong></td>
          <td>Analgesic / Antipyretic</td>
          <td>Adjunct pain management — allows reduced opioid use (opioid-sparing effect). Max dose: 4 g/day (3 g/day in hepatic impairment or chronic alcohol use). Do not combine with other acetaminophen-containing products. Monitor liver function if prolonged use.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- APPENDIX B: Q&A -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="appendix-b">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Appendix B</span>
      <h2>Post-Simulation Questions &amp; Answers</h2>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q1: Which patient statement indicates PCA teaching has been effective?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content"><p><strong>"I feel less anxious about the possibility of overdosing."</strong> The PCA's lockout interval and 4-hour maximum limit are specifically designed to prevent overdose. A patient who understands these safety mechanisms is more likely to use the PCA appropriately and achieve adequate pain control. Patients should not wait for severe pain (7–8/10) and should not rely on family to press the button for them.</p></div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q2: Lou's PCA is running but she says her pain is still 8/10. What are the priority actions?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ol>
          <li>Assess pain character, location, and severity — is this the same surgical pain or a new problem?</li>
          <li>Check PCA pump — is it powered on? Is the tubing connected and patent? Is medication remaining in syringe?</li>
          <li>Check demand dose history — is the patient pressing the button? Are doses being delivered (or is lockout preventing delivery)?</li>
          <li>Assess IV site for infiltration — medication cannot be delivered through an infiltrated site</li>
          <li>Review current order — is the dose appropriate for Lou's pain level?</li>
          <li>Notify provider if pain remains uncontrolled after troubleshooting — request dose adjustment or supplemental analgesia order</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q3: Lou's respiratory rate drops to 8 and she is difficult to arouse. What is the priority action?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content"><p><strong>Stop the PCA pump immediately.</strong> Then stimulate the patient (call name, sternal rub), apply supplemental oxygen, assess SpO₂, administer naloxone (Narcan) 0.4–2 mg IV as ordered, and call for help / activate rapid response if unresponsive. Document all findings and notify the provider. Do not restart PCA without a new order.</p></div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q4: What are the signs of fluid volume deficit in a postoperative patient?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ul>
          <li>Urine output &lt; 30 mL/hr (earliest sign)</li>
          <li>Dark yellow or amber, concentrated urine</li>
          <li>Tachycardia (compensatory)</li>
          <li>Hypotension — may be orthostatic initially</li>
          <li>Dry mucous membranes, dry skin</li>
          <li>Weight loss (1 kg = 1 L of fluid)</li>
          <li>Elevated BUN / BUN:creatinine ratio &gt; 20:1</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q5: What is the first sign that GI function is returning after colon resection?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content"><p><strong>Passage of flatus (gas).</strong> Flatus indicates that peristalsis has resumed in the large intestine. This is the key clinical marker that permits diet advancement from NPO to clear liquids. Return of bowel sounds alone is not sufficient — the nurse must also confirm the patient has passed gas before initiating oral intake.</p></div>
    </details>
  </div>

